Setup system:

In our course - Test Automation with Selenium WebDriver 3 using Java, we will use new Selenium WebDriver 3.
 
Selenium is a set of different software tools each with a different approach to supporting browser automation.
These tools are highly flexible, allowing many options for locating and manipulating elements within a browser, and one of its key features is the support for automating multiple browser platforms.
 
Here is a prerequisite:
 
1. Selenium WebDriver 3 uses Java 8. Please install/upgrade the version of your Java to 1.8
 
Download:
macOS:                        jdk-8u172-macosx-x64.dmg
Windows 64-bit:         jdk-8u172-windows-x64.exe
 
2. Install Maven 3.5.3
 
Download:                               apache-maven-3.5.3
 
2. Install new version of Eclipse IDE for Java Developers - Oxygen.3a
 
Download:
macOS:                        eclipse-inst-mac64.tar.gz
PC:                               eclipse-inst-win64.exe
 
3. Upgrade all your browsers:
 
macOS:
Firefox - 60.0.1
Google Chrome - 66.0.3359.181
Safari 11.1 (12605.1.33.1.4)
 
4 Upgrade all your browsers:
 
PC:  
Firefox - 60.0.1
Google Chrome - 66.0.3359.181
Internet Explorer 11.0
MS Edge 17.17134
 
5. Download the following Drivers:
 
macOS:
Mozilla (Firefox) GeckoDriver 0.20.1:  geckodriver-v0.20.1-macos.tar.gz
Google Chrome Driver 2.38:                chromedriver_mac64.zip
 
PC:
Mozilla GeckoDriver 0.20.1:                geckodriver-v0.20.1-win64.zip
Google Chrome Driver 2.38:                chromedriver_win32.zip
Internet Explorer Driver:                    IEDriverServer_x64_3.12.0.zip
Microsoft Edge Driver Release 17134:MicrosoftWebDriver.exe
 
6. Configure Safari + WebDriver: read
 
macOS:
Opening Safari preferences (Safari > Preferences in the menu bar),
Going to the Advanced tab and ensuring that the Show Develop menu in menu bar checkbox is checked.
Allow Remote Automation in the menu bar.

